      Did Elon Musk manipulate Dogecoin?
   =20
 =20

Dogecoin is a tradable electronic=C2=A0token representing the value of Elon=
 Musk=E2=80=99s attention. When Elon Musk tweets about Dogecoin, its price =
goes up. When he goes on =E2=80=9CSaturday Night Live=E2=80=9D and makes pa=
inful jokes about Dogecoin, its value goes up.
  [1]
=C2=A0When Elon Musk does not shine the bright light of his attention on Do=
gecoin, its value drifts down.=C2=A0
This is not entirely=C2=A0true =E2=80=94=C2=A0somebody traded Dogecoin even=
 before Elon Musk paid attention to it =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it=E2=80=99s a re=
asonable model. It is not investment advice, though it does seem to have be=
en a large part of  the investing approach=C2=A0of Alameda Research, which =
was a multibillion-dollar crypto trading firm for a while. If you are a cry=
pto hedge fund, or a retail crypto trader, this model would suggest that yo=
u should buy Dogecoin just before Musk tweets about it and sell it a bit af=
ter he tweets, but that=E2=80=99s hard (you have to know when he=E2=80=99ll=
 tweet). A second-best model might be to buy Dogecoin shortly after Musk tw=
eets about it and then sell it a bit later, and that does seem to  have bee=
n Alameda=E2=80=99s approach.
But what if you are Elon Musk? A thing exists in the world whose value depe=
nds entirely on Elon Musk=E2=80=99s tweets, and you are Elon Musk. What is =
the trade here, for you? I mean! From first principles:
=09Buy a ton of it.=09Tweet about it.=09Sell a ton of it.

This is almost too dumb to write because the opportunity=C2=A0is so obvious=
, but at the same time the opportunity is so rare that you might somehow no=
t think of it. I   once wrote about this trade that it was as though someon=
e handed Musk a lamp and told him there was a genie inside of it, and that =
=E2=80=9Cany time you want the price of [Dogecoin] to go up or down by 10% =
or more, you can just whisper =E2=80=98price go up=E2=80=99 or =E2=80=98pri=
ce go down=E2=80=99 into the lamp, and it will happen instantly. You are th=
e only person who can do this, and you can do it as often as you want=E2=80=
=9D:
I just think that if you presented this possibility to any famous investor =
throughout history they would absolutely faint with excitement. And here Mu=
sk is, the second-richest person in the world, either doing it =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0in which case it=E2=80=99s one of the greatest trades, and also one of t=
he greatest trolls, in history =E2=80=94=C2=A0or=C2=A0not=C2=A0doing it, ru=
bbing the lamp and making Bitcoin and Dogecoin go up and down and up and do=
wn and up and down with his whims,=C2=A0just=C2=A0for fun, leaving billions=
 of dollars of profit on the table because he doesn=E2=80=99t need the mone=
y and has the purest imaginable commitment to internet trolling.
Oh yeah: I assumed that Musk was=C2=A0not=C2=A0doing this obvious trade.=C2=
=A0He was certainly tweeting about Dogecoin, and he had certainly bought so=
me Dogecoin, but I just figured that he was not in fact optimizing his fina=
ncial returns on the trading-plus-tweeting.=C2=A0He was busy running Tesla =
and SpaceX and the tunnel thing and probably several other companies at the=
 time (this was pre-Twitter); his whole schtick was about building stuff, n=
ot just dumb manipulation of meaningless abstract financial markets. Still =
the opportunity was so obvious!
Anyway here=E2=80=99s an amazing lawsuit claiming=C2=A0he was manipulating =
Dogecoin to make money:

This is a securities fraud class action arising from a deliberate course of=
 carnival barking market manipulation and insider trading by the world=E2=
=80=99s richest man Elon Musk, who hijacked an emergent pop-culture phenome=
non to cross-promote himself and his companies, and to pad his obscene fort=
une, preying on the earnest hopes of vulnerable Americans, including war ve=
terans, blue collar workers, and the elderly. ...
Musk=E2=80=99s followers did exactly what he said. Musk=E2=80=99s pretense =
that promotion of Dogecoin was just well-meaning fun=E2=80=94not meant to b=
e taken seriously=E2=80=94is not credible. It is Musk=E2=80=99s custom=C2=
=A0to publicly address serious topics glibly on Twitter. That doesn=E2=80=
=99t make him any less serious. Musk knows that the bulk of his followers a=
re not sophisticated in business or investment, and Musk uses this knowledg=
e to manipulate them. Musk is what is called an apex predator, feeding on a=
nd manipulating the hordes below, including his Twitter following which has=
 grown to 141 million.

The complaint claims that he made $10.2 billion of profit on Dogecoin from =
just one of his several wallets, an amount that is bigger than=C2=A0the ent=
ire current market capitalization of Dogecoin. (Which makes sense: If Dogec=
oin is valued based on Musk=E2=80=99s attention, he should have extracted m=
ore than it is currently worth.) Also=C2=A0it is just a big number? Like if=
 you went to Elon Musk and said =E2=80=9Chere is a dumb thing that you coul=
d do to make $100 million in 10 minutes,=E2=80=9D he might reasonably say=
=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cnah I have so much money, $100 million is not enough to make=
 me spend 10 minutes doing a dumb thing.=E2=80=9D But $10 billion is so=C2=
=A0much more money than that! If you went=C2=A0to Elon Musk and said=C2=A0=
=E2=80=9Cyou can do some dumb tweets to make $10 billion,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0mig=
ht he say yes?
Now, there are some problems with this lawsuit.
  [2]
=C2=A0The most obvious problem is that the wallet the plaintiffs have ident=
ified =E2=80=94=C2=A0the one that made $10.2 billion of profits trading Dog=
ecoin based on Musk=E2=80=99s tweets, and that at one point held over $25 b=
illion of Dogecoin=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0probably does not actually belong=C2=
=A0to him. The evidence that the plaintiffs cite is pretty thin:

Dogecoin wallet DH5yaieqoZN36fDVciNyRueRGvGLR3mr7L (=E2=80=9CDH5ya=E2=80=9D=
) also belongs to Defendant Musk. ...=C2=A0On February 10, 2021, Musk tweet=
ed that he had purchased Dogecoin for his son. =E2=80=A6 The previous day, =
DH5ya (which was then the world=E2=80=99s largest Dogecoin wallet, containi=
ng roughly $2.8 billion worth of Dogecoin) placed a transaction for 28.0619=
71 Dogecoins, the numeric equivalent of Defendant Musk=E2=80=99s date of bi=
rth, i.e., the 28th of June 1971. This wallet would purchase Dogecoin in th=
at same amount on February 10, 2021, and once again on February 17th. =E2=
=80=A6
