<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When I was an investment banker, a guy joined =
our desk as a vice president from another bank. He had several months of ga=
rdening leave =E2=80=94=C2=A0enforced, paid time off due to his noncompete =
agreement with his prior bank =E2=80=94=C2=A0and then started working on ou=
r desk. He lasted, in my memory, a few months, and then left to go back to =
his old bank, after another period of gardening leave. We all thought he wa=
s a genius. Really the best possible job, it seemed to me at the time, was =
getting paid an investment banking salary for=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>doing =
investment banking. If you could just yo-yo back and forth between banks, t=
aking six months of paid time off each time you moved, that seemed ideal. O=
thers might disagree, and I was not, to be fair, a very good or ambitious i=
nvestment banker.=C2=A0Maximizing gardening leave is not really a path to b=
ecoming a master of the universe. But it seemed nice.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you work at a financial services firm and y=
ou go to your boss and say =E2=80=9CI am taking a job offer at a competitor=
, they are going to pay me $2 million a year,=E2=80=9D your boss might say =
=E2=80=9Cno, stay, we=E2=80=99ll pay you $2.25 million.=E2=80=9D For a high=
 performer, money can be matched. But if going to the competitor gets you s=
ix months=E2=80=99 gardening leave, that might be a good reason to leave an=
yway. Can your boss match that? Well I mean sure, why not. Bloomberg=E2=80=
=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31696643.2674=
18/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDYtMDEvdG9w=
LXRyYWRlcnMtc2VlLTEyMC1taWxsaW9uLXBheWRheXMtYXMtaGVkZ2UtZnVuZHMtZmlnaHQtZm9=
yLXRhbGVudD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNjA1MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV=
9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA2MDUmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1Z=
mY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB704de21f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  Nishant Kumar reported last=
 week</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When portfolio manager David Lipner said he wa=
s quitting billionaire Izzy Englander=E2=80=99s Millennium Management to jo=
in a rival, the hedge fund countered with an unusual proposal: A one-year p=
aid sabbatical and an incentive upon return if Lipner stayed.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And stay he did. For Millennium, the $58 billi=
on industry giant known for ruthlessly cutting underperformers, the generou=
s offer was seen as totally worth it. After all, Lipner had made money for =
the firm for more than a decade, longer than most hedge funds remain in bus=
iness.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Such enticements are now becoming part of a gr=
owing array of expensive tools the world=E2=80=99s biggest hedge funds are =
deploying to hire and retain traders.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Oh of course if you are an ambitious successfu=
l portfolio manager you are not really switching jobs to get gardening leav=
e; probably you are <em>annoyed=C2=A0</em>about the gardening leave. The ar=
ticle is mostly about how multistrategy funds are offering huge amounts of=
=C2=A0<em>money</em>=C2=A0to star performers:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Last year, a senior portfolio manager was lure=
d by a major New York fund with more than $120 million in guaranteed payout=
s, according to a headhunter who said he=E2=80=99d done several deals payin=
g north of $50 million. Contracts worth $10 million to $15 million are incr=
easingly becoming common for traders, said another.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Hedge funds have long been the land of eye-pop=
ping rewards, but a few recent trends are converging to take it to new leve=
ls. The stellar track record of several giant firms that spread money acros=
s teams of traders following multiple strategies has caused their assets to=
 surge. That=E2=80=99s prompted a hiring spree to add more traders and stra=
tegies so the existing ones aren=E2=80=99t over-stretched.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But =E2=80=9CLipner wasn=E2=80=99t the only on=
e offered the sabbatical by Millennium.=E2=80=9D Not working at a hedge fun=
d does seem to be a highly desirable perk among people who work at hedge fu=
nds.</p>
